{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ξῠρόν</b>, τό, <br /> <b>razor,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 241, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 65, “Th.” 219, 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “Alexipharmaca” 411, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Artoxerxes” 29, etc.: proverbial, ἐπὶ ξυροῦ ἵσταται ἀκμῆς.., ὄλεθρος ἠὲ βιῶναι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] death or life is balanced on a <b>razor's</b> edge, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.173 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: frequently in later authors, to express a delicately balanced like lihood of failure or success, ἀκμᾶς ἑστακυῖαν ἐπὶ ξυροῦ Ἑλλάδα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 97; ἐπὶ ξ. γὰρ ἀκμῆς ἔχεται ἡμῖν τὰ πρήγματα 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.11; κίνδυνος ἐπὶ ξ. ἵσταται ἀκμῆς 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 557; βεβὼς.. ἐπὶ ξ. τύχης 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 996 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; ἔβητ᾽ ἐπὶ ξ.; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 630; ἐπὶ ξ. εἶναι 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 22.6; ἐπὶ ξ. ἑστηκέναι 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “JTr.” 3. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8434","accentedUnicode":"ξυρόν","shortDef":"a razor","mediumDef":"a razor","stepGloss":"a razor","stepTransliteration":"xuron","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}